\section{Stage structured matrices}
Everything that we have discussed for age based matrice so far also holds for stage structured populations. The main difference between the two is that an age based matrix only know two types of transitions: due to survival, individuals in age class $a$ can only get into age class $a+1$ at the next time step. The only other possible contribution is due to reproduction, which allows a contribution from age class $a$ to the first age class. It is impossibe however, for individuals from age class $a$ to end up in age class $a+2$ after one time step (you can not get two years older in one year of time!). It is also not possible to stay in the same age class! Hence, a lot of transition rates are $0$ in such matrices.

When we instead classify a population in stages rather than ages, we do not have this property anymore. Say we have three stages: small individuals, medium-sized individuals and big individuals. Due to extreme growth, a small individual might become a big individual after one time step, or maybe it doesn't grow at all and it might stay small. Furthermore maybe a big individual may, after a harsh winter with almost no food, become a medium-size individual. Hence, much less matrix elements will be zero. 

In the following exercise we are going to look at a stage structured population. Here, we only look at a $2\times 2$ matrix, but for larger matrices the same procedure can be followed, leading to the same conclusions about the dominant eigenvector and the stable stage distribution.
